{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9ee8633e-b976-40e7-82fb-cabb6fa6ff1c","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to them:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |\n\nOther useful events: `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding` (iOS/Mac only).\n\nAlternatively, you can subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, etc., for a pattern closer to the old override style.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bb4544cc-d5fa-4705-a069-7532961609aa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event (or override `OnCreated`)\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Backgrounding` event\n\n\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Activated` or `Window.Resumed` event\n\nThe key difference is that the `Application` class no longer has those lifecycle overrides. Instead, I need to override `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class and work with the `Window` lifecycle events directly, or create a custom `Window` subclass. The main window events I'm working with are `Created` when the window initializes, `Activated` when it comes to the foreground, and `Deactivated` when it loses focus.\n\nThe complete mapping is straightforward: `OnStart()` becomes `Window.Created`, `OnSleep()` maps to `Window.Stopped` or `Deactivated` depending on the platform, and `OnResume()` becomes `Window.Resumed` or `Activated`.","outputTokens":763,"requestId":"9426:2C549C:1444090:16B24B1:6A067114"},"id":"1e04afa8-e6b8-4f68-957b-02d3bbbda6ed","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:33.566Z","parentId":"e80c4e4a-a690-4e64-8347-304785d12bac"}
